those modes of thought which most exclude plants. The most hierarchical systems typically put plants at the bottom, but Hall finds much to support a more positive view of plants. Indeed, some indigenous animisms actually recognize plants as relational, intelligent beings who are the appropriate recipeints of care and respect. New scientific findings encourage this perspective, revealing that plants possess many of the capacities of sentience and mentality traditionally denied them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBotany -- Philosophy. 0aBotanyxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Philosophy. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Environment and Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143843430840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438434308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438434308/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles